    <statement><p>Find the <m>y</m>-intercept and any <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of the quadratic curve.</p>
<p><m>{y}={-23x-24-5x^{2}}</m></p>
<p><m>y</m>-intercept: <fillin characters="16" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><m>x</m>-intercept(s): <fillin characters="17" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,-24\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(-1.6,0\right), \left(-3,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>We need to change the parabola to standard form first:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {y} = {-5x^{2}-23x-24} }</m></p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into <m>{y}={-5x^{2}-23x-24}</m>, and we have <m>y=-24</m>.</p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,-24)</m>.</p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y=0</m> into <m>{y}={-5x^{2}-23x-24}</m>, and then solve for <m>x</m>.</p>
<p>For this problem, once we factor out the leading negative one, notice that the polynomial can be factored:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = {-5x^{2}-23x-24} \\
   0 \amp = {-5x^{2}-23x-24} \\
   0 \amp = -({5x^{2}+23x+24}) \\
   0 \amp = -(5x+8)(x + 3) \\
   5x+8 = 0     \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x + 3 = 0 \\
   5x      = -8 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x = -3 \\
   x          = -1.6 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x = -3
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercepts are <m>(-1.6,0)</m> and <m>(-3,0)</m>.</p>
</solution>
